reviewText: Ordered this for a school lesson and the kids loved it! The characters were lively and the lessons were easy to understand. Would purchase again!

The Proud Family Movie is a 2005 Disney Channel original movie based on the classic animated series starring an great voice cast including Kyla Pratt, Tommy Davidson, Paula Jai White and JoMarie Payton. In this film, Penny Proud(Pratt)just turned 16 and wanted to spend her birthday with her friends at a rap concert, but her dad(Davidson)refuses to let her go to the concert. Instead, the Prouds are headed for a vacation on a tropical island by invitation, however, it was a plot by a descendant of George Washington Carver in his evil plan to steal the dad's secret formula. The result is the Prouds gets involved in many hilarious situations. The special features includes episodes clips of the Proud Family show, as well as a Penny's Driver's Ed. game and sneak peeks of other Disney DVD favourites like Phil of the Future and That's So Raven. The Proud Family Movie is one of the best and most memorable Disney Channel movies to enjoy!

I was very surprised to see so much disrespect towards parents, foolishness and stereotypical African American characters.  It may have a nice ending, but the end does not justify the means.  I'll never know, my own brown American children of mixed ancestral heritage suggested we actually turn it off about a third of the movie in.  So we did.  That's how we are in my family and in other black families I know. I'd much rather watch old episodes of Fat Albert.  Disney would do well to catch up to that classic or create movies the likes of The Golden Blaze or the absolutely beautiful Prince's Quest.  It shouldn't be that difficult to create a film or animation that features black Americans in an honorable fashion.  Selma, Lord Selma was very well done as was Cinderella with Whitney Houston.  Even the Princess and the Frog has some pros and cons.  But this? My 7 year old said it right..."the Proud family has nothing to be proud of"  I guess we're just not a pop Disney kind of family.

I tried to view this movie with my 8 year old dtr. I used to watch the series with her brothers when they were young and enjoyed it, but the movie was differrent. We had to turn it off because of the extremely negative sterotyping, poor (not bad)  language, and themes that were not age appropriate. My son who is 16 now was listening, not watching and he was so disgusted at the content he heard, he said he did not want her to see or hear that. We spent the next 1/2 in discussion refuting the messaging that parents are idiots, the father should not try to protect the morality of his children, parents pitted against each other is okay, and it's okay at 16 to: lie to your parents, sneak out of the house, dress in revealing clothes, etc.  Yup its just a cartoon but we need to elevate the thinking of our children, honor the family, refute behavior that is exploitive.
